news_header: U.S. crude oil inventories rose significantly last week, exceeding expectations.
news_original_title: U.S. Crude Oil Inventories Surge Much More Than Expected
news_text: The Energy Information Administration reported that U.S. crude oil inventories increased by 8.7 million barrels for the week ending January 31, much higher than the expected 3.2 million barrels. Current inventories stand at 423.8 million barrels, about 5% below the five-year average. Gasoline inventories also rose by 2.2 million barrels, while distillate fuel inventories fell by 5.5 million barrels, which is around 12% below the five-year average.
